15 Years Anlysis¶

We went through stock market data, license application data, and unemployment data for the recent 15 years to do analysis

  • We found there are not much significant relationship for the 15 years data analysis
  • Therefore we repeat the process for a 5-year analysis at the end, the result is slightly different

Variations in the Stock Market¶

  • We analyze the stock market trend, and ploted the trend line in the high price and low price
  • We see the high price and low price are sharing the same trend from 2003 to 2017
  • We find out that the 2003 has the lowest stock price and 2016 has the highest stock price in this 15-year range

We run OLS regression on the merged license data and stock market data¶

We conclude that 15 years license data and stock market data have significant relationship¶

  • As p value 0.017 smaller than 0.05 we observe There is statistical significant relationship between these two data
  • We also oberserved a very small R-squared value: 0.002, which means there are very little variables are explained by this regression model
  • When we only run regression with high price and number of application, we have a p-vale of 0.008 which indicates a significant relationship. Though R-squared value hold the same

In order to see a more recent trend, we did another analysis over the past 5 years later again, to see the relationship between license data and stock market data.¶

Fifteen years high stock market price have significant relationship with license application¶

We see the p-value=0.008, and t-value=2.659, therefore we conlude there is significant relationship between Business license application and High stock price. As the stock market price goes up, the license application number goes up by 0.0016 high price. As this coefficient is very low and there is an extreme outlier, the relationship is not obvious when look at the plot

  • We also observed stock market high price have significant relationship with business license in the 5-year analysis.
  • Therefore we conclude that in the 5-year data the stock market price also have significant relationship with license application

Plot stock market HIGH price and the number of license application relationship

We run regression on all three datasets: Unemployment rate & Stock Market Price & number of license application. We got the same result as the anlaysis above.¶

We found there is significant relationship between unemployment and stock market price, but there is no relationship between unemployment and license application.¶

  • while holding the number of license application fixed, we see the p-value for the high price is 0.000, also we see the t-value is -4.195. So we conclude there is significant negative relationship between unemployment rate and high stock market price, because of the small P-value and large t-value
  • while holding high stock market price fixed, we see the p-value for the number of license application is 0.358, also we see the t-value is 0.922. So we conclude no significant relationship between unemployment rate and number of license application, because of the large P-value and small t-value
  • We also observed the R-squared is a very small number, very little variable is explained by this regression model
